{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"87b16325-5094-4663-8463-12f7d4cc2aae","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws<T>` (xUnit/NUnit) instead:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n}\n```\n\n**Why switch?**\n- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws, masking bugs (e.g., the constructor could throw instead of `CreateUser`).\n- `Assert.ThrowsException` pins the exception to the exact call.\n- You can also capture and inspect the exception:\n\n```csharp\nvar ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n    () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\nAssert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName);\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"82547548-239c-4f18-a6ba-64a4a39ce722","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":279,"requestId":"983E:24244F:1010077:144BD43:69FFDFFE"},"id":"afdc0215-7716-4280-9f9f-0bc09e4c70b1","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:31:48.870Z","parentId":"2cb273c9-1516-4e6b-802a-8636b2bdef4b"}
